Clearly not. The creature merely hissed and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost her grip on its too smooth scales.
"HOW DO YOU KILL THEM ?", shouted Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD !"
"THAT'S NOT GOING TO BE EASY !"
Thassalin exhaled, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed him, somewhat panicked when a flash of fire struck her from behind. The creature hadn't noticed that she was no longer alone. Her panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then violently hit her head with his tail, causing her to veer off her path.
Growling and hissing, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster was absorbing the light of the sky and replacing it with a perpetual cloud of night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin tried to retreat, but he scraped the tops of the trees before crashing into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in her wake.
"Kayel !", exclaimed Tenuk as he extricated himself from the cloud and began flying in circles to try to locate Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What do we do, Kayel ? Kayel... ? Kayel, where are you ?"
Down below, Nyssi struggled to get up. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, unnatural healing powers had already started to take effect. The same could not be said for Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try and reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see more than two meters ahead of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by the impious shadows. And within those shadows, something was screaming.
An horrible club-shaped tail came swinging down beside Nyssi, knocking her off her feet. She noticed, however, that the tail was swishing around, not targeting her. The creature, from the little that Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and clawing at the shadows she had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster, disorienting it.
A gunshot suddenly rang out, and the monster collapsed silently, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, holding the rifle and breathing heavily.
"This... is the weirdest shadow leap I've ever done... Thanto kat'olon...", gasped Kayel. His eyes gleamed with a dark light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow hue.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, as most people considered them impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed quite surprised himself.
"Are you okay ?", Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm okay. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work as Tenuk made his way to land beside him, returning to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slick, but the mucus continued to adhere to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what this thing was, something howled and lunged from a nearby bush. However, the beast didn't have time to reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, throwing it at Nyssi's feet. Taking no chances, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature instantly.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily cutting the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you all right?"
"You practically missed all the action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all left me behind. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "May I know what those contemptible things are?"
Retvik's question fortunately received an answer from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut up and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too hurt.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible god monster that we... helped kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. EXACTLY. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO AIM FOR THEIR HEADS. I'M MISSING A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE, IT'S NOT FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked toward Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS CAPABLE OF KILLING UNIVERSes."
"Uh... thanks... I guess", said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then grabbed her camera to photograph the beasts, now thoroughly dead. She then took out her favorite dagger, the one of the god of death, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns, before moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures caught fire and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
"Well... that's both convenient and not convenient at all," she sighed. "At least I still have the photos..."
